I agreed with you last summer upon watching this, now just finishing watching OUATIH last night and know I couldn't disagree with you more. The fact is the viewer doesn't and shouldn't go into this film looking for a tense riveting narrative - the subject matter is the Hollywood industry, it's not Inglorious Bastards or Kill Bill. There's more than enough tension in the film anyway and as for the 2nd act you're knocking on - that has the now iconic "Spahn Ranch house" scene with Cliff and the creepy Manson acolytes and of course the hugely satisfying climax at Rick Dalton's house. The film was perfectly paced. Are you saying you want tension and high drama stress in your films for 160mins? Inglorious Bastards wasn't like that either inbetween the moments of extreme violence. As what you say, I don't know anyone that has seen this film and thought it was boring, you ought to give your fans more credit if you believe that. People that go to watch this film or types of it are genuine lovers of film and will fall in love with the long gone era of late 1960s Los Angeles that's brilliantly depicted. Non films fans just wouldn't watch something like that and for that length of time.
Also, in defense of Robbie, she grounded the reality of the film for me. She was the actress who was settled into the normal life. But it’s the normal life that brought those tense scenes for me.

Considering "tension" - The whole film is permeated with tension. As the plot unfolds casually, there is always this lingering presence of Sharon Tate, who embodies that tension because most viewers at least have a vague knowledge of what happened to her historically (at least I would hope so). It made it so that for me personally, it was impossible to fully relax into what I was seeing without a slightly uncomfortable feeling in the pit of my stomach. I can't agree with your assessment of the Spahn Ranch scene being "blehh". The buildup is wonderful and the release is a subversion of the million things the viewer is expecting and dreading happening to Cliff. It's actually one of my favorite scenes, personally. Love the review overall and agree the film isn't perfect, but personally, I thought the lingering tension was masterfully spread thin throughout the entire experience.

An insightful review but I saw this movie from a different angle.  I was 18 in the summer of 69 and the Manson family murders really shocked the country.  In the pre-internet era we weren't inundated with 24/7 real crime news stories and there were very few mass murders then.  So I felt a low voltage tension right from scene 1 in the theater.  Knowing Tarantino's penchant for graphic depiction of violence didn't help.  Being immersed in the sights and sounds of the late 60's again was kind of a thrill and Quentin's choice of tunes was fine.  So, strapped in for the ride, it was just a question of how much the director was going to manipulate the viewer leading up to the horrific crime.  What you saw as a comedy film I saw as a slow, uneasy descent to hell.  The whole thing was like being in a roller coaster ride that you were told in advance had mechanical issues.  I think Tarantino made the film assuming the audience had some historical grasp of the gravity of the crime on which the movie was premised.  That throws a whole different  perception of the yellow brick road of songs, quirky characters, and humor he adorns the film with.  The brief smile flashed by the Charles Manson character summed up the movie for me.
I think the only reason Chris didn’t think this movie didn’t have enough tension was because he didn’t know the Sharon Tate story very well going in

I was disappointed with the Bruce Lee scene. I don't understand why Tarantino had to turn Bruce Lee into a cocky, dumb asshole just because it was an "alternate reality a la Tarantino." What was the point of it? To show how macho and charismatic Brad Pitt is? Even though Brad Pitt is playing a character, it is still Brad Pitt's interpretation of that character. The audience sees Brad Pitt more than the character. So I don't understand why Tarantino had to turn Bruce lee into an asshole so Brad Pitt can mock and beat him. All of this may not have mattered if there was no negative Asian male stereotyping in Hollywood, but that is not the case. Asian male stereotyping has been around for decades – Asian men are bad guys, weaklings, foreigners, or kung fu characters. And now Tarantino had turned Bruce Lee, who had tried so hard to rid those negative Asian male stereotypes, into a jerk who got his ass handed to him by a white male sex symbol. Tarantino should have consulted Shannon Lee beforehand, but he didn't give a damn. It would have been a great film, but that scene killed it for me.

Your insight towards the end, about how we have been trained to want everything right now, that every scene needs purpose is a really telling one. I think this may be a reason why we may struggle when watching this movie. There are however, other factors, and I think your right on tension. This film has none of it. 
. Characters feel like they are going round, without any fear, precondition or urgency, everything is so chill, so relaxed, theres no plot in this film, theres no struggle. There are no stakes, and its because of this that the film can at times be quite taxing. 
There are however, moments when the movie really shinres. Leonardo’s story, from falling during his first audition, to picking himself back up and succeeding is one of tarantino’s most poignant ever scenes and could be the mostmoving of his scenes.

I suppose a person would have to be of a certain age to appreciate the build up to the Manson murders. I was only 2 years old when it happened, and I am from TN, but those murders were so horrific that it cast a dark shadow all over the whole nation, nay- the entire world. It was something that my family just did not speak about, and when something came up on the news about it, my Mother would sob quietly. My WWII Navy Vet Grandfather loathed the mention of a "no good hippie/gypsy", and as I grew up and learned of what happened, I understood why. It was this tear in modern day polite society. It was the very worst horror movie come to life. It is why the world turns a blind eye to any idiosyncrasy, legal or illegal, that Roman Polanski may, or may not, be guilty of perpetrating- after what was done to his wife and unborn child. You have to understand this, in your gut, in your bones marrow, to know how Quentin was playing with the audience's emotions- like they were on a yo-yo. This movie just absolutely blew me away, perfection. The alternate ending was like a gift to me. A wonderfully violent and bloody gift that makes all things right in the world, like only a fairytale ending can! "A+"

I'm a big Tarantino fan, but did I miss something? I just watched this the other night and found it an incredibly boring, 5/10 movie. Good performances, yes (Pitt was phenomenal, Leo was great, and that little 8yo girl was fantastic). Good cinematography, yes. Good script, yes. However, Margot Robbie's character was incredibly underused. And why was so much time spent on multiple scenes that went absolutely nowhere? The final 10 minutes of the movie should have come 30min earlier. 

*Examples...*
When Sharon (Robbie) went into the theater and watched her movie, why did we have to sit and watch that for 10min? Or when Cliff drives, why do we have to see everywhere he goes? Or when Cliff went to the Manson farm, why was there all that build up for some big reveal to just have it lead to nothing? Or when Cliff and Rick spend a good 10min sitting in front of a tv, examining their performances in past roles, why did we have to watch that?

Don't get me wrong, I love a good slow-burn movie when it's executed well. I just found myself more frustrated with scenes that acted like they would go somewhere, and then just drop off. I see so much wasted potential in this movie, and there's no reason it should be over 2hrs long.

A+. This comedy drama is Quentin Tarantino at his best. It's fresh, original and tragically funny. It's a beautifully finished period film, mixing history and fiction in a cool entertaining way that is also thought provoking and even inspirational in the end... Once Upon a Time in Hollywood is a montage of life in 1969 Los Angeles, and its huge expanse of city life and urban sprawl. It focuses on seemingly disconnected characters whose lives end up converging together in an epic way... Sharon Tate, a real life character, was at the center of the movie start to finish. So, of course the actress who portrayed her had to be in the movie! Chris. What did you want, an all-guy movie?.. In the end the fictional characters of Rick and Cliff came to her rescue, which rewrote history, and it was the best feel good moment I've experienced watching a movie in a long time. I hope to see more rewriting of tragic history in more movies... Chris brought up all that time spent at the Charles Manson ranch, and how it seemed to go nowhere??? IT WAS THE CHARLES MANSON RANCH. Cliff definitely WENT somewhere, Chris, and I didn't fear for the Bruce Dern character. I feared for Cliff... My God, if Cliff discovered a dead George Spahn, that would have been the end of Cliff, and the movie. So were expectations subverted?.. NO... CLIFF PAID A VISIT AT THE CHARLES MANSON RANCH surrounded by brainwashed maniacs. Expectations exceeded, right there, and that was before Cliff beat the shit out of one of those hippie pieces of shit, and drove out of there alive in his friend's beautiful 1966 Cadillac coupe DeVille... Tarantino had a very clear vision, and he put this movie together methodically. Nothing in the movie happened for no particular reason. Tarantino wasn't just goofing around with the camera one afternoon in L.A., spending many millions of other people's money, just having fun... Chris, can I ask you something?.. Are you in any way related to Doug DeMuro?

Quentin Tarantino's movies are known for mundane conversations that manage to absorb the viewer. His ability to write good dialogue is usually the main reason. In ONCE UPON A TIME IN HOLLYWOOD, the main reason is how the actors deliver their lines. Not that they were badly written or anything, but there are no memorable quotes. Fred Raskin's editing is weird (and not in the cool way it's intended). Kurt Russell's narration comes and goes without any rhyme or reason and, several times, he redundantly mentions a date or time while an on-screen text is showing it. Whenever a period piece shows archive footage to provide context, it normally takes about 2 seconds. That's enough for the viewer to recognize the clip. Here, they're shown for much longer. In some cases, the scene from a movie or TV episode is almost played in its entirety. I know Quentin likes to pay homage, but there's no point in that if it's going to ruin the pacing. Not to mention that his strenght is taking elements from other works and adding his own style. Let's play a game. Imagine placing the climax of INGLOURIOUS BASTERDS onto PULP FICTION. It wouldn't fit, right? That's this movie in a nutshell. We get over 2 hours of different people who are somehow connected doing all sorts of things without that much plot progression, but time flies by thanks to the writing, directing and acting. There's even a very long sequence about a fictional TV show. I was so invested that I kind of forgot I was watching actors playing actors playing characters. I will say that the tone and especially the camera work and editing felt too modern for a TV pilot in 1969. Anyway, the climax is an over-the-top gore fest that reveals that this is an alternate timeline. It's fun to watch, but a "This was just a slice of life" ending would've been more appropriate. Unlike I.B., there are no layers of depth (like the bittersweet irony of a person sacrificing themselves to kill Nazis without killing the specific Nazi they wanted to get revenge on) or an ambiguety on how the future will be affected. It's a revisionist fantasy for the sake of it that has a clear outcome. The villains experience a violent encounter, but it felt to me that the women received a more brutal treatment than the man. Coincidence?

Just watched the movie and came here to check the review. Spoilers: Personally, I really enjoyed the film and it's casual vibe (I was expecting a lot more scenes, an Inglorious Basterds kinda pacing), but I don't think it had enough depth to justify the run time.

They could have made the ranch scene shorter and cut some other stuff and the very insulting Bruce Lee scene, the narration was weird and the narrative too loose.


 The acting by Leo and Brad was top notch, one showing struggle while another showing swagger and Margot brought a certain innocence to Sharon's role but I wish she had more to do. Leo yelling while sipping a margarita was hilarious. Even the supporting performances by the Manson family members were amazing. 

The last 20 minutes of the film and that fictional twist was interesting. On one hand, the idea of a sweet ending where Sharon and her friends survive that horrendous incident would hit any viewer right in the feels. On a humour basis, Brad vs. Manson Family was the best scene of the film. But at the same time it seems like the movie manipulates you, because you're bearing through the slowee scenes to see how Tarentino deals with the murder scene. But he replaces it with this crazy fight scene and gives a fairy tale ending, which also seems like a cop out somehow.

Overall, certainly not as good a Tarentino film as Pulp Fiction or Kill Bill, but better than Kill Bill vol. 2 and Hateful Eight, it's up there with Djnago Unchained and Inglorious Basterds.

OT - If i was to give you script notes,


Quentin, I love what you have done here. This script sings a love for Hollywood that leaps off the page. I like that you're changing history again and I think that this mixed genre thing you've got going on could work really well.

I do have some issues however.

One of the things I look forward to in your screenplays are the hidden coincidental connections and clever foreshadowing of events to come. e.g - "Garcon coffee!" or "Pai Mei taught you the five point palm exploding heart technique?"

I know you really wanted to do 'a day in the life' of these characters, but the lack of connections between these stories makes for some uninteresting set-ups that never quite pay off.

1. Steve McQueen sets up the relationship between Jay Sebring and Roman Polanski, but we never see or hear from him again.

2. Bruce Lee and Cliff Booth fight, but we don't get a resolution?

3. If the Manson Family gets killed before they murder anyone, Charles Manson will never be implicated in the murder and he will still be out there.

4. Jay Sebring is clearly trying to get back with Sharon and Roman is cool with him hanging around all the time?

5. The Western TV show with Rick was cool, but he goes and acts in a Sergio Corbucci film we never see?

Now, I'm no Oscar winning writer, so take this with a grain of pepper...

What if you scrap the TV Western scene and convert it to a sequence in Italy showing Rick working with Sergio Corbucci on Nebraska Jim. Nebraska Jim is a success and when Rick comes back on a high, he finds an invite in the mail to Sharon Tate's party.

Rick and Cliff Booth head to the party, and as they walk up to the gate, Bruce Lee and Steve McQueen pull up in a red Ferrari (I am sure you know this, but they were good friends in real life. Bruce was his trainer and Steve was an accomplished martial artist). Bruce and Cliff have words before they speed off up the driveway and into the party.

At the party Jay Sebring spots Rick and they have that interaction you wrote at the end where they talk about his body of work, showing Jays appreciation for Rick as an actor. Sharing their mutual love of pop culture, Cliff, Rick and Jay become friends and make some drinks together.

Steve McQueen and Bruce Lee chat to Sharon Tate when Roman Polanski comes bursting in pissed at Jay for trying to steal his pregnant wife.

Outside the Manson family members (Tex, Pussy, Sadie, Patricia and Linda Kasabian) pull up with Charlie in the driver's seat. They all smoke acid dipped cigarettes (except Charlie, who pretends to).

Charlie runs them through his plan once again, making sure everyone knows what they have to do. They get out of the car and Linda Kasabian has second thoughts. She makes a run for it, leaving them with a part of the plan missing - Charlie now has to go in with them.

Jay and Roman are about to get physical. Rick and Cliff stand on the side of Jay, and Steve and Bruce side with Roman.

It's about to get nasty when Sharon's stands in the middle trying to break them apart. They start to fight, Sharon's water breaks and she goes into labor.

BANG! A gun fires in the air and five Manson family members (Including Charlie - who is holding the gun) walk into the party.

Charlie gives one of your famous monologues about his distaste for the entertainment industry, and the Mexican stand-off begins.

In an awesome Kill-Bill-esk kung fu fight, Bruce, Steve, Rick and Cliff take down all the Manson family members.

Only Charlie remains. He's had the gun the whole time, but has shown his true colors and been too afraid to use it.

Bruce, Rick, Cliff and Steve all begin to converge on Charlie. He who knows he's done for, so he turns the gun on himself and pulls the trigger - CLICK! he's out of bullets.

In a Death-Proof-esk ending, Cliff, Rick, Bruce and Steve take him to pieces.

Sharon gives birth, and Roman and Jay make up.

In a post credits scene (because they're all the rage these days) we see Rick, Cliff, Steve and Bruce working together on Game of Death - The movie Bruce Lee never finished.

Just a suggestion.

Hope it goes well for you.

Honestly, with regard to your point on the lack of tension in the second act - many many points in the film (for me) almost felt like he was toying with many of our expectations of Tarantino’s films. 

Take the old house scene you talked about that ends a bit deflated, it gave you the feeling that CLEARLY something was GOING to happen...and it’s going to be BLOODY and SINISTER. But....actually - “oh so cynical! She was telling the truth! Were you expecting violence??” I got the image of him laughing at us while we watched, expecting Tarantino style violence. 

Then.....the end..............GOOD GOD. I was approaching discomfort with the level of violence. Especially with who the majority of it was aimed at in today’s climate. Like it was a “OK, here you, here’s the violence you’ve been waiting for! Don’t complain! This is what you wanted!!”

I just got the feeling at so many different points that he was really having fun and using our expectations to his advantage. It felt like a film that was almost more for his entertainment than for ours (in reference to those points, there was obviously more to the film than that).

Still, good review, as per usual 👍

The good thing is that even for people who don’t know the details of the Manson murders and the names of the victims and who Sharon was, there are still enough entertaining moments and characters to keep audiences interested. Now the bad thing is that since they don’t know about where the movie is headed, there’s no real suspense. Just more watching characters do stuff. But for me, the moment Rick said his neighbor was Roman Polanski when he saw him and Sharon, the seed of dread was planted in my stomach and the whole movie I was just waiting to see how Tarantino would handle the murders. I should have seen the ending coming after what he did to Hitler in Inglourious Basterds, but I still did not expect that at all 😂😂😂😂

If you know a little more about Sharon than just the fact that she was murdered by the Mansons, you’d know that she was an actress just barely getting her big start. That whole bit with her at the movie theatre watching her own movie, where it took the employees awhile to recognize her, makes sense when you get that she was up and coming. It’s to show how new and fresh she was to Hollywood and still so excited about starring in movies and seeing herself on the big screen and wanting to be recognized, then Tarantino set that as a direct contrast to two hard boiled past their prime stars, and I understand that while she didn’t have much to do, it gave you some context as to just how much was actually lost when she died. Not only were her and her baby killed, but also her blossoming career so we’ll never know if she could have become another famous icon.

I tend to agree with you on most of your reviews. In this case, I strongly disagree with you on two points. Firstly, as far as Act Two, I found it incredibly anxiety producing, almost as much as the last scene. Secondly, Sharon’s character is not incidental. Tarantino almost makes it sound like he wanted part of the film to be an homage to her life and what was stolen from her. That is why he chooses to portray her as a sweet, regular person, doing regular things any of us might do: dining out, listening to music at home, hanging out with friends. Even if I hadn’t heard Tarantino talk about her so affectionately, I kept thinking, over and over, how heinous her murder was, especially in contrast to her sweetness. I saw her for the first time as a real, flesh and blood woman, rather than as a ghost from the past.

I think part of the reason Margot Robbie doesn’t do much and yet is present throughout the movie is to contrast the bright-eyed optimist at the beginning of her career with the faded star of Rick Dalton, and to keep building up the tension based on what the audience already knows about the Manson murders. Personally, the first of these worked really well, but the second one relies too much on Tarantino assuming the audience already knows what happened to Tate. The better version of this tension-building process is when we see Manson as he visits the Tate house, because it’s the only time we see him despite his weight hanging over the rest of the movie (a bit like the shark in Jaws was my first thought). And the ever-present Manson women all over LA probably achieves that tension-building better than the Tate stuff. Probably the sequence of Tate in the cinema could have been cut, but then again it did allow Tarantino to get some prime feet shots, and we all know how much he enjoys those!

I am 24 years old and don't live in the US, hence the whole Manson murdering these Hollywood celebrities was something unknown to me. I see this movie as something similar to *"A joke that I didn't get"*. I'm not saying this movie is a joke, rather one of those things that would've had a greater effect on me if I related to or knew who these characters were.

After seeing it I used the argument that a lot of classics are hangout movies. GoodFellas or Trainspotting for example. Henry only flips into an informant in the last 30 mins. The junkies only set up the drug deal & Renton only betrays them in the last 15 mins. The Manson aspect in this is just thrown in during the last chunk, but like those movies, it’s in no way solely ABOUT those things.

Everyone saying that Chris is wrong to say Sharon didn’t feel relevant to the plot: Obviously she needed to be in the story to execute the whole Manson element and have the satisfying ending of Rick and Cliff preventing a murder spree without even knowing. What he means is that Sharon as a character was empty and pointless we didn’t get to know her at all, she existed purely for the Manson murder near miss gag and was completely empty as a character for all the screen time she got.

WARNING SPOILERS AHEAD: I went in to this thinking the Sharon Tate murder would be shown in some way or another, i just hoped it wasn't to graphic since it's based on something that really happened. But when Rick approached the "hippies" in the car i started to realize where it was going. It's a complete alternate reality where Cliff Booth and Rick Dalton altered what actually happened in real-life. The fact she wasn't killed in this alternate reality and that the actual killers got what they deserved makes the ending so beautiful and sentimental, and to be honest it makes the whole film for me. Furthermore the fact that Rick realizes he wasn't so irrelevant after all given Sharon Tate's friend recognized him and most importantly Sharon Tate even knows his name was very endearing. I'd give the film an 8.5/10.

I feel as though the Spahn Ranch / Bruce Dern sequence is pretty integral to the theme of the film. Leo's character is shooting a western whilst Brad's character is living out his own very real western simultaneously. The small town, the onlooking bystanders, the supposed murder mystery. (Spoilers) then to only discover Bruce's character is living quite comfortably tells us Rick and Cliff are truly at odds with the rapid change of Hollywood. This "hippie" era is here to stay and they no longer have a place, cemented by Bruce Dern's sleepy "leave me alone" stance. Rick sees his own future in a cowboy book, whilst Cliff sees his in the eyes of an old man, adopted by Manson's followers, foreshadowing the ultimate explosive outcome of both Hollywood and the film.

Spoilers obviously.


1: This is probably the only Tarantino movie I have no desire to see again.
2: This movie is probably/unfortunately dependent on the audience having the knowledge of what actually happened to Sharon Tate.
3: I will pose that this entire, long film is about 1 moment. The flip.


All of Tarantinos movies have violence in them. As far as I remember all of the violence in earlier movies is either funny, justified or both. This one is different.
As the movie went on, and especially when the 4 mansoners drove up to Ricks estate I was dreading the finale. I think partly because all of Sharon/Margots scenes have been innocent and happy. I didnt want to watch the ending, and I honestly thought Tarantino would just make a historical movie and show us the murder. I dreaded it. The violence or the expectation of it felt horrible and wrong.


Then they enter the wrong house, Brad/Cliff greets them...and the movie flips for the first and only time. Instead of being horrified at a stupid and horrible murder....we cheer as the villains are slaughtered. I dont think I have ever experienced an expectation be flipped that fast and that brutally. 


Also...in the aftermath I was thinking of what the manson girl said in the car. "We grew up watching TV and it taught us murder. Lets murder the ones who taught us murder" Or something like that.
The ending of the movie have Rick being invited up for drinks at Sharon. The only ones suffering from violence in this picture are the violent villains. It might be a bit on the nose, but that felt like a message to me.


It was quite a thoughtful movie, but also less engaging than most Tarantino flicks. The setup was very long, with less payoff than usual. That might have made the last payoff (the flip) be felt that much stronger, I dont know. As usual it was something unique. But when you know the flip, the entire movie kinda loses its luster for second viewings. Like the sixth sense. And its too long to be enjoyed more than once I think.

Every time I see a Tarantino movie in the theater I feel this tingle and my absolute love for the movies has been rekindled. For me this movie had this affect for me. As well made as this movie was, I don't quite know how to feel about it. I like that it tells a story about an actor struggling to remain relevant in a Hollywood that is changing. But I find it odd how Tarantino tries to rewrite real historical events. Like killing Hitler and thus prematurely ending World War II in Inglourious Basterds, Tarantino rewrites the Manson murders here, and I just don't know what he's trying to say or do when he makes such historical changes. It's one thing to present actual events in a twisted Tarantino way, but it's another thing entirely to take an eraser to it and say "Nah, it didn't happen at all" when we all know what happened. The Manson murders and the aftermath also reflected the change in Hollywood in that era, but by altering those events, it almosts feels like Tarantino is negating those real-life cultural changes, which would in turn seem to negate Rick Dalton's career struggles throughout the movie, which is the primary focus of the film. So you reach the end and say to yourself "Well that whole fight and the flame thrower business was a blast, but what's the point of the movie now?"

Tarantino is that guy that sat glued to the TV and there are so many references to shows that he devoured, some say that the Rick Dalton character was partly based on Pete Duel from Alias Smith and Jones, who battled with depression, alcoholism and eventually died of a self inflicted gunshot wound to his head. Rick Dalton in a soliloquy threatens to blow his brains out after messing up his lines due to consuming eight whiskey sours the night before.
A rumour is that Gene LeBell did in fact manhandle Bruce Lee on the set of The Green Lantern, substitute Cliff Booth for Gene mixed in with a bit of Paul Newman and Hal Needham, who was Burt Reynolds stuntman and you have Brad Pitt's character.
Acting in this film is off the charts, forget about Margot Robbie not having many lines what about Roman Polanski one of the most influential Directors ever, I think he had one sentence in the entire movie.
Scenes and Dialogue have not been wasted in this film, would be interesting to know if Tarantino will release a Directors Cut with material that has been cut from this particular film.

I wish I could plug the other comment that broke down why Stuckmann is wrong, but to add to what he said, the film is playing our expectations against us. Tarantino is famous for subverting the expectations cinema has built into us, and with this film, he subverts the expectations of what we've come to expect from him. The Spahn Ranch scene is one of Tarantino's best because he keeps us locked to our seats with incredible tension because we expect a terrible outcome. And he keeps twisting the knife, stretching that rubber band from when he arrives at the ranch to entering the house to beating up the hippie. Tarantino knows what we expect from a Quentin Tarantino film, and instead of delivering what we expected, he gives us a loving, thoughtful, endearing, and tender portrait of an era that ended tragically. It's the last thing we'd expect Tarantino to make, and it was brilliant in all the right ways. And I fundamentally disagree with Stuckmann's statement that this isn't Tarantino's best movie. It's very much his best movie, but in the same way that The Social Network is David Fincher's best movie. It's his most well realized film, in every aspect, from the directing to the writing, to the acting, pacing, and soundtrack. It wont be his most influential film, same with Fincher (Pulp Fiction and Fight Club respectively take those spots), and most likely not even his most enduring film

*SPOILERS*

(something the movie comments on with the ending conversation between Rick and Sharon and Jay Sebring), which Tarantino is clearly aware of, but that doesn't mean it isn't his best work. Tarantino himself even stated that this film is his magnum opus, and I'd be hard pressed to disagree. It's a brilliant, inspired, near flawless movie that, at the very least, reminds us of what movies should be and is a true Hollywood masterpiece, something rarer and rarer since the 70s. All in all, the best film of the year so far, and should be respected as Tarantino's best as well.

Just walked out of the theater a few hours ago and me and one other friend turned to each other and said “I don’t get it.” 
Don’t get me wrong, I throughly enjoyed the film but I had no idea what I was getting into with this Tarantino film. I watched the trailer right before entering the theater, not that I need a trailer to see a fucking Tarantino film but just to dip my feet and prepare myself. 
Another friend with me told me that Charles Manson was involved in a small way. And that’s where the movie went right over my head. My knowledge of Charles Manson is slim to none. I know a little, straining the little, about Charles Manson. I knew he had a cult following, I knew about satanic murders and whatnot but I’ve never seen a documentary and I’ve never read up on him. 
So I’m watching the film and I’m watching the character of Sharon Tate and I have no idea why she’s in the movie. Im waiting and waiting and waiting for these characters to cross path, which SPOILERS, does not happen until the end of the movie. And I’m misunderstanding what the plot is, and especially what the end goal of the movie is. The ending happens and it was amazing in every Tarantino way and the characters finally interact and the credits start to roll. I’m thinking “that’s it, all that buildup for him finally to get his old stardom back and we don’t get to see it?” 
It was like I was waiting the whole movie for the movie to start, y’know? So I called my dad because he wanted to hear my thoughts before he watches it. I explain my grievances when he explains to me that in real life, everyone was killed by those Manson cultists. Without that knowledge, all the tension with Margot robbies character was completely lost to me. I didn’t get it because I didn’t know about the real life event it’s based on. That kind of bugs me because he’s doing the same thing with Inglorious Basterds by retelling history but unlike inglorious basterds, I had no idea what history he was retelling. It severely impacted my enjoyment and understanding of what this movie is. Because I was watching it thinking everything was fiction, not grounded in some form of reality. Don’t get me wrong, my lack of personal knowledge is by no means the fault of anyone but me, but I wish someone would’ve told me what this movie was actually about, which the trailer didn’t give me, so I could’ve done some research. So I could’ve learned about the brutal murder that Tarantino decided to rewrite. I still thought it was a great film but if I could change anything about my first viewing or anyone’s first viewing is to learn about the murder the movie is leading toward because without that you’ve got no tension and, from my perspective anyway, no story.

!*!*!*!*!*!*! SPOILER ALERT (kinda...) !*!*!*!*!*!*!
Saw it the other day; it was particularly ironic, sitting in the theatre, listening to the audience laugh away at the ending, while (I'm assuming), most (a young Taiwanese audience, in my case; but I imagine this can apply to many of the audiences that will eventually see this film) not knowing the actual history of the event that this film precludes ... it's not a "happy ending", but rather the "beginning of a horror show". That feeling was interesting throughout the final 'showdown' scene, as I didn't know when or whether Brad Pitt's face was going to be blown off, or Francesca get gutted ... kinda freaky queasy feelings in my stomach...
I guess the climax could be seen as a foreshadow technique to the horrors to come.But again, without context, what then is accomplished, except the graphic act in itself? And, despite Tarantino's obligatory "style", I think if that was the objective (a foreshadow technique), it could / would have been accomplished much more subtly with even greater effect (as, in my opinion, evidenced by the Spahn Ranch scene).
But then, it could be that Tarantino is simply providing alternative history (a parallel universe) where the Manson Family murders are in fact thwarted, by the actions of that night over at Dalton's house... ??? And it IS a "happy ending", after all.
But if that's the case, why? We spend 3 hours waiting for his "joke" ending? That's a little self-indulgent, even for Tarantino ... Why not go full-bore fantasy land, instead of such exacting detail in all other accounts of that period of TV and film specifically, and L.A. generally?
In the end, a "story" still ought to be a "story", in any art form. I think Tarantino lost the "story" in this one somewhere along the way... maybe even from the beginning, just in order to justify his ending, which seems to have come first to his consciousness.
(There's mention on the film's Wikipedia page of Pitt originally being cast as the investigating officer of the crimes ... Wait, WHAT? So the crimes DID happen; or DIDN'T happen; or ... Ah, now there's some potential evidence of Tarantino no being sure himself as he was developing the script, leading to the mess that I'm describing here!
"and that Pitt was in talks to portray the detective investigating the murders." - Wikipedia Page)
Beyond that, if one isn't old enough (or researched enough) into that particular time period (let alone the cultural gap I refer to regarding sitting in a theatre full of young Taiwanese of which I'm guessing the vast majority can't even relate to Sharon Tate and related murders history the ending hinges on!), then despite the craft of the acting, directing, cinematography, et al, most of the film's script (thus significant humour) would simply be a complete waste of time and effort and energy and commitment and ... 
Now, (I guess ???) luckily, I did grow up watching Manix and Lancer, Steve McQueen and The Rifleman, the influence of spaghetti westerns on pop-culture, reading Kid Colt comics, etc. So I (like others of my generation) can appreciate the innumerable humorous references written into the film. But I couldn't help understanding as I sat watching this, how many people wouldn't. Again, is the film made to appease Tarantino's self-interests and indulgences? Obviously, to a great degree.
But here may lie a valid critical argument: Make the thing and stick it in your basement then. Or show it to some buddies / peers who are going to get it, even. But is that art? Is "art" self-indulgence, or is "art" a means to communicate something to an audience? Tarantino seems to think the former is far more important than the latter. And to me, it's to a fault.

That right there should subvert your expectations you're not going to get what you think and that's what makes Quentin top tier as a director, he slowly built up literally everything for the finale and it payed off.. We were always told that the Manson family were monsters and evil beyond belief, whereas Quentin wanted you to have the two main heroes not GIVE A FUCK and be able to make them their bitch.. I fucking loved that, I loved that Rick and Cliff were so far and away capable of quick thinking! Why? Let me explain


Rick Dalton was in the movie constantly obsessing over small details, he tried to remember everything important and constantly loved re-watching and re-living his movies.. So what did he remember when the moment came to life or death? "Oh yeah! I got a fuckin flamethrower prop from my Nazi movie!" Absolutely loved how Rick was really in a way a genius.

Cliff is a man with absolutely nothing to lose, The Manson family fed on fear and they became confused and frightened by Cliff's nonchalant attitude to even the most tense situations.. He was, in a way, their kryptonite because he wasn't even in the slightest afraid of Bruce Lee so do you think he would be of frightened by a bunch of loser psycho kids? Fuck NO! 


The more I think about this movie, the more I'm in a awe of the way Quentin built tension only for it to go nowhere most of the movie and why is that? Well it's fiction! I have no previous feeling toward Tarantino and went in with pretty much no expectations.  The movie dragged for the first 90% essentially and I was super confused with the brutal ending.  It wasn't until my husband explained that there were the Manson murders in 1969 that I realized what a gem the film really was.  The movie seemed to me like a character study of these two men whose careers and lives are burning out.  Rick says he feels useless, like he doesn't add anything to the world, and his stunt double is essentially in the same situation, only even worse because he's also about to lose his job of driving Rick around.  Even the audience gets to a place where we almost stop rooting for Rick, especially because he's kind of a tool.  And then, bam, these two characters who are deemed "useless" inadvertently stop this major Hollywood murder that, as someone else in the comments said, essentially brought about the end of the Golden Age of Hollywood.  It's the most epic, "What if?" because it doesn't ask you to believe that Rick and his stunt double are heroes -- they're a hot mess like most of humanity -- but in that moment, they change a horrible event in history.  Moreover, Tarantino didn't just kill the Manson murderers.  He had their demises met in the most gruesome ways possible.  There's no question as to who the villain is, even if Rick is the asshole for most of the movie.  Someone else in the comments said that it's Tarantino's middle finger to the Mansons, and that's exactly how I watched it.
So, on the whole, the context really does it for me.  The movie was long and tedious, but the payoff was incredible.

Disagree on Margot Robbie's role. She's crucial for building tension, crucial to show why its worth being an actor in the first place, and she evens out the emotional core of the film by giving some space from Pitt and Leo's darker story line. If she wasn't in the movie, the ending wouldn't have worked and people would've said it was disrespectful to Sharon Tate. If Tarantino did give her more of his sort of dialogue, people would've said it was disrespectful too.

The cinema scenes with her are probably the ones that had to carry the most narrative weight in the film (Yes, even more than any of Pitt or Leo's). It's subtle, but it develops her character, sets up stakes in relation to who we'll lose when the historical events happen (since most people know the murder but not who she was), shows why it's 'worth it' for actors by juxtaposing with the scene of Leo flubbing his lines and going off on himself, her interaction with Bruce Lee inter-cut with the scene is used to balance his portrayal since the first one was negative but necessary to set up the final confrontation's plausibility, and brings us away from the behind-the-scenes of Hollywood to see how it interacts with the world at large - which is later integral to contrast with how The Family believes Hollywood has affected the world. It wasn't a glamorous scene to act like Leo gets on the set of Lancer or Pitt gets in a couple places, but it's the scene that makes the movie work as a meta-narrative (which is the point of the film) and the other scenes with Margot Robbie are necessary to make this important scene work in the narrative. This movie would've been bloated with any more story lines to try 'giving Margot Robbie more to do' (which is dumb, she already accomplishes the thesis of the movie) and cutting Margot Robbie from the movie substantially would either make it not make sense or take away the broader purpose of the film.

I think people might not have had time to process the movie fully and that's why we're seeing so many people think Margot Robbie wasn't doing much. It's also a difficult scene to 'get' since it's done with next to no dialogue to contrast with the dialogue-driven scenes going on with Leo on the set of Lancer. It also doesn't help how the scenes with Leo on lunch break, flubbing his lines, then his 'dark Hamlet' scene are immediately gratifying in relation to Leo's character arc at that point in the story where Robbie's scenes are busy laying the groundwork for something that takes the entire film to pay off.

Ok Chris. Love your channel. Agree with most of your reviews. I have a bit of a bone to pick with you on this one. You, like 95% of the other reviews of Once Upon A Time....have misunderstood the role of Margot Robbie (Sharon Tate) in the plot. You say she doesn't have much to do. Or much to say. Maybe she's not important to the plot?


Her performance is critical. Her lack of dialogue is intentional. She is portrayed as the Icon of Hollywood at that time. She's a beautiful woman, nice to all and she serves as a bridge. She's the connection between the old Hollywood we see dying out & the new "hippy" style that is taking over. It would eventually die out itself but not before ushering in the 1970s. 


Too much dialogue for her would skew the viewer to have an opinion that perhaps she isn't someone worthy of being saved at the end of the film. Playing an Icon is difficult but Robbie pulls it off almost perfectly. We see her as totally sumpathetic. The audience going in, is probably going to know that she is a murder victim to the Manson family. Her portrayal is as a shining beautiful person WORTHY of being saved. Too much dialogue would probably spoil that. 


I agree totally with how Tarantino wrote that character.  It's similar to the decision NOT to show if Cliff (Pitt) really did kill his wife. We are supposed to bond with him throughout the movie so we can root for him the last 15 minutes. By not showing more of that scene of him on the boat with his wife, Tarantino is telling us that he probably did not kill her. He puts up with his bad reputation on movie sets because he doesn't feel he has to justify something he's not guilty of. I saw parallels between him & Tate in this film. 


She's above the fray. Dialogue would just bring her down into it.

Films in the 60’s and 70’s and before then had scenes that weren’t integral to the plot but gave you more about the character’s, small human moments. Films since the 80’s have become more processed less about human moments and more about a very fast pace and lots of action. I like slower films that draw you in and aren’t all action and mindless characters.

This is one of those rare movies that really only works great for a specific audience.
If you didn't grow up during this era of American culture, or if you aren't a major Hollywood scholar/mogul, you probably aren't going to get as much out of this movie as Tarantino's other works, even if you really love his work as a director and writer.
I'm 22 years old, and I went to see this movie with my parents. When the movie ended, I didn't really see what was so great about it, but after a conversation with my mom, who grew up during this era, I got a better understanding of just how important the Manson murders actually were to that generation, and how much they changed life and culture in America. For a lot of people who grew up around this period, the revision of the Manson murders that Tarantino pulls off is kind of like if someone made a movie thirty years from now about the 9/11 hijackers, and had them just miserably bungle the whole thing up and get their asses deservedly handed to them, leading to a cathartic happy ending that we sadly didn't get in real life. It's a revision of a real-life event that had a traumatic effect on the American consciousness, and Tarantino wanted to rewrite history to have a happy ending like in the old movies he loves, which is actually kind of sweet when you think about it.
Unfortunately, people younger than, say, 30-40 probably won't get much out of this. All the references and nostalgia would have little effect because it's of too early an era, and the revision of the Manson murders doesn't have the same impact for younger audiences because we've all grown up in the post-Manson murder world, where macabre violence and cynicism in both life and entertainment are both ubiquitous. We see mass shootings and murders and rapes and all manner of unspeakable horrors every single day, and we've never really known that idyllic world where people felt safe to leave their front doors unlocked at night. Going into it with this context in mind might help people appreciate the movie more, but most probably won't go into it with that context.
And really, even with all of that taken into account, it's still not one of Tarantino's best movies. It doesn't have the same innovation, energy, conflict, eclecticism, or imagination as his best works do. Granted, it still has a lot of those elements, just not as much as say Kill Bill, Pulp Fiction, or Inglorious Basterds. As a matter of fact, pretty much every element of this film, while still really great, feels watered down from his best works. And considering the 3-hour runtime on top of all of that, I can't say it's a movie I would see more than once.

Theory on Sharon Tate's involvement. 
She is the example of someone who's just stoked to even be in a film. Even a small role, and a comedic role. She loved the slight reaction the audience was giving her in the theater. She was so happy to be in the Playboy mansion, and had a completely wholesome and innocent vibe the entire film. This to me was to contrast the difference in actors here. Leo's character is basically pissed hes no longer the biggest action star going and is trying to get a movie with one of the best directors in Hollywood and is still crumbling at the thought of only being a secondary character.

I believe the entire point of these seemingly meaningless scenes with Margot were to purely show the other side of Hollywood. Some people are genuinely excited to be on screen, be known by a small amount of people and are quite fine being a side character, which is exactly what Margot is in this film.

That being said, they certainly could have given her a few more lines at least. I think he did all of this purposely but I'm not sure it completely worked for me either.

So I’m kind of surprised by Chris and Angry Joes reaction to this film. Some of the complaints like Margot Robbie as Sharon Tate not being important to the narrative, and the film lacking tension indicate they missed Tarantino’s point. Going into the film Tarantino expects us be aware in 1969 Sharon Tate was murdered by the Manson family and based on his previous work that murder will likely be the climax of the film.  This is foreshadowed throughout the film, like when we learn Rick lives next door to Sharon and how Cliff keeps running into one of the Manson girls, eventually taking her home to their camp.  Theres supposed to be a slow building tension as these things play out.  The natural conclusion is Rick and Cliff are likely to get caught in the cross hairs and more than likely be punished for their brazen disrespect of the Manson clan.  Rick in the driveway the night of the murder and cliff when he visits their campsite and beats up the guy who flattened his tire.  The acid dipped cigarette, Rick and cliff getting drunk. It’s all meant to create tension, for us to worry they won’t be able to put up a fight During the inevitable Sharon Tate murder scene. Notice how they put time stamps on the screen the night of the attack. We’re supposed to think this is a recreation of the real murder. Until the fairy tale reversal. Cliff runs into one of the Manson girls a few times and eventually ends up taking her to their camp. I felt this tension and sense of anticipation throughout the whole film. Then we get the beautiful and satisfying ending when he flips our expectations and cliff and Rick end up inadvertently saving the day and rewriting history.  Tarantino wants us to think this film is doomed to follow real life history with Rick and Cliff caught in the crossfire.  The film is basically a fairy tale (hence the title) where Tarantino’s fictional characters essentially have supernatural strength and ability.  Like how Cliff put up an even fight with Bruce lee. In real life Cliff would have gotten his ass kicked by Bruce. But here, these characters are like Tarantino childhood movie heroes.  He was 6 years old in 1969 and looked up these types of actors and performers (Rick and Cliff) like kids today look up to iron man and captain America.  So in this fantasy fairy tale his movie heroes have supernatural strength and ability.

I don't think enough people are talking about how expertly Tarantino had his audience exactly where he wanted once shit went down in the final act.

Chris: I loved Once Upon A Time In Hollywood, but it is about something. It is not just a collection of scenes. OUATIH is about Tarantino's current struggles with aging, or his mid-life crisis. Despite DiCaprio playing an actor, he is supposed to be Tarantino of today; an aging artist in Hollywood who has passed their youthful heyday, is uncertain about their future, and doesn't know what to do next. Margo Robbie's Sharon Tate is actually Tarantino of the 1990s, a contrast to DiCaprio. Robbie, like Tarantino during the days of Pulp Fiction, is filled with happiness and optimism about the future. I think you have misinterpreted her character. She isn't required to do much other than to show playfulness (dancing at the Playboy Mansion) or happiness/joy (seeing her own movie on a screen). Again, the whole point of her character is to symbolize that younger Tarantino. She isn't just there because of the Manson subplot.

Once Upon a Time in Hollywood is such a unique film going experience. The meticulous recreation of 1969 Hollywood and the brilliant sweeping shots Tarantino uses to romanticize it is endlessly fascinating. Tarantino finally examines the melancholy side of nostalgia and the result is heartwarming and powerful. It is not a movie for everyone. It’s a slow burn that’s deliberately paced but teases the inevitable shocking ending every step of the way. I loved it. A masterclass of direction. I do think it lacks Tarantino’s signature dialogue though. I needed my Jules/Vincent “Royale with Cheese”, “Foot massage”, “Walk the earth” scenes between Pitt/DiCaprio that showed their bromance on fully display. The movie also needed more DaKota Fanning (who is remarkable in her one scene), Margot Robbie (the heart and soul of the movie), and Margaret Qualley (explosively temptous and creepy at the same time). That woulda made it the perfect movie.

I understand there’s a lot of misdirection in the movie but I don’t think it’s an excuse to just leave plot threads open. [spoilers ahead] for example the scene where brad Pitt is on the boat with his wife. We never get payoff to that. Maybe it was meant so we can draw our own interpretation of “did he kill her” but why leave that up to us? It’s a vital character point and we as an audience have to decide if this guy is a deranged killer or not? We see Manson once but in the end it’s just his goons that come to kill them. I get that it’s probably more accurate that way but this movie is throwing accuracy away. At that point we should just never seen Manson at all and let him be a background figure. The guy at the playboy mansion watching Tate and being creepy never goes anywhere. I’m happy they gave te a happy ending but in this fictional world I want to see that “what if” scenario go further. I wanna see if she was never murdered how well does her life go. The one girl that stole the killers car and fled doesn’t do anything for the story except maybe because she left that’s why the other three failed but if that’s the case that only works for people who know details about the murders to an extreme detail. Everything with Margot robbies Tate was wasted for a misdirect. Clearly he wanted to set it up so we think we are attached because we think she’s gonna die, but she doesn’t and in the end she isn’t even involved in the final conflict, so what’s the point. If she would have been in the house when everything went down it would have made so much more sense why we would care for her because we would be afraid for her. But really her buying a book and watching herself in a movie and training with Bruce lee are all pointless scenes because her character is the equivalent of a family guy cut away gag. “Remember that time this lady got murdered” it’s pointless. I understand the point of this movie. I understand who it’s for, but fundamentally it is a bad movie. It has great moments, and if it just stayed focused on the main two characters and cut a lot of the unnecessary stuff, it would be so much better. Hell the ending scene was amazing but even it is just random. Why not have them coming as revenge that Pitt beat up their friend. That makes so much more sense why they’d attack that house. Instead apparently Manson gives them that order, but they ignore that order and go for decaprio for some reason. It’s just a mess and they should have cut the fat and stayed focused.

If a generation ever comes when all or most stories follow one specific flow or structure, I'd consider that a generation of stagnation. Storytelling at its core is an EXPERIENCE, not just a business or trend.

Change is almost never easy but it's a necessary risk (to a point). Peaks & valleys are inevitable in any medium but I'd never want us to stay in one place forever, even if that place were the highest peak. 

The day our society forsakes creativity for consistency is a day I don't look forward to, because it'd come across to me as our culture sending a selfish message of "We're satisfied, just let the art die".

The more thought I give to his work, the less I like Tarantino's films.  His whole career has become a giant, self-aggrandizing eye-roll to me. I can understand why people enjoy his films. He can write the hell out of a bit of dialogue and he creates interesting characters (peaked with Hans Landa and Aldo), but it all feels so superficial. Again, I understand why people enjoy his films, especially someone like Chris, who can appreciate the hmm... "texture" of Tarantino's film making, and that's enough to make the run-time spent on it worthwhile to him. 

But listen to the review. A second act that's meandering and potentially uninteresting, even lazy. Not enough build-up, a lack of tension. A character with major screen time whom Chris feels could be written out. Which to me is made all the more egregious by the fact Margot Robbie's character seemingly does nothing of import. She is literally just a pretty face for the viewer to gawk at. I can already see some of the pitchforks that will get raised at that. Sharon Tate was a rising star. She was a person. She had agency. She DID things. If Robbie's role in this is so inconsequential, couldn't it be argued that the use of Tate's name is a bit exploitative? If she has no bearing on the film, yet is in so much of it, then what was Tarantino trying to do with the character? After all, this was an intentional decision by Tarantino, but I wonder if it will back fire with some of the audience. I found this quote of him talking about how he portrayed Tate in his movie:

"Unfortunately, she’s kind of been defined by her murder. I thought the best way to get her across was not sticking her in a bunch of scenes with Roman or with other people where she’s [furthering] a plot, but just hanging out with her, letting her drive around Los Angeles, do her errands, and just see where the day takes her. I wanted to show people a glimpse of Sharon before the murder, so they think of her as more than just a victim."

So my question is, could she have been named anything else and still have had the same impact on the film and by extension, the audience? Will people walk out and feel that Tate's been redefined in their minds? Or will they just think, "that was a great movie, and Margot Robbie was beautiful in it but didn't do much did she?" In short, will it MATTER that Margot Robbie's character was Sharon Tate? It'll be interesting to go into the movie with that in mind, see how it plays out.

Like with so much of Tarantino's film making, I understand where he's coming from and what he's trying to do, but I just don't know if his execution works. So yeah, I can understand the A- Chris is giving the film. It comes from an appreciation of Tarantino as a film maker, and the artistry on display in his films. But for me, artistry and a very apparent love of film just aren't enough. The same way that gratuitous violence masking a thinly veiled attempt at making a statement isn't enough for me with films like Django Unchained, Inglorious Basterds, or The Hateful Eight. The same way that his penchant for paying homage to his heroes isn't enough for me anymore in films like Kill Bill or Pulp Fiction. 

I've initially enjoyed most of Tarantino's films. But any examination of his films always makes me feel like Tarantino's just a pretentious dick, who's more concerned with painting himself as an edgy art house maestro than with actually making a good film. For me, there's just a massive disconnect between what he says about film (particularly his own films), and what his films turn out to be. I've watched all of his films multiple times, precisely because I can see nuggets of stuff that I really enjoy, even if the overall work just doesn't do it for me. Even if I hate his work in general, I feel that it still merits examination. There's a reason so many people connect with his stuff. I'm just not convinced that he's the master film maker that people make him out to be.

Though to Chris' point, I'll probably go see this movie just to see DiCaprio and Pitt work off of each other, if nothing else. As I said earlier, Tarantino can write some really great dialogue. So I'd be down to pay $10 to watch two of my favorite actors banter with each other. But I can already tell that while I'll probably enjoy the performances, I'm going to dislike the film overall. But who knows, maybe this is the one that hits the mark for me. I do enjoy hangout movies.

I can appreciate that people will enjoy this...but it doesn't sound like my bag.  From the review it sounds like the humor is more "real life" rather than movie humor....meaning humor sounds like something you would laugh at if you actually saw/heard it happen in real life, but since this is a film I expect more.  I have a higher standard for humor in movies....to come up with a "funny line"  spur of the moment in real life is difficult and therefore my expectation (what I will subconsciously accept as "funny") is lower.  But in a movie, they have time to craft and create and redo to make sure everything-- dialogue, phrasing, timing, etc is perfect and I expect that level of humor in my movies.  I could hear something in real life and crack up laughing...but if I heard that same line in a movie I might only give a little smile.  My expectations are higher for movies...I appreciate the crafting of the joke, and the art and care of crafting that joke is a huge part of what actually makes it funny for me.  Funny in real life is not nearly good enough to be funny in movies.
Again, I'm sure some people will love this, but it doesn't sound like my type of comedy.

I haven't seen the movie yet, but a comment about Margot Robbie in this movie. I'm 64 years old, and saw movies in the 1960s. In that period (also in years prior and then yet to come) beautiful women were used as set dressing and a draw for men to be attracted to the exceedingly silly movies if that era. The use of THE WRECKING CREW and Sharon Tate's clumsy and artless slapstick antics was a perfect  example of this. I can picture Tarantino using Robbie as a nod to that era, as well as a sign of that era coming to an end, along with the horrendous murders committed by the Manson clan as well being the harsh slap of reality. Just my 2¢.

Narrative in films is not required unless you're trying to tell a specific story. But if you're not, all you need is a place or a situation and BOOM, you have your setting to write scenes for.
Robert Altman's Nashville is about a time and place and the country music scene in the 70's, but what's the film about? A political rally in Nashville and all the press people and
various odd characters who happen to live or show up there. That's it. And it's regarded as a masterpiece.
Or what about some of Fellini's films? La Dolce Vita, 8 1/2 and City of Women are based on nothing but feminist, absurdist and satirical ideas, but they're absolutely spellbinding as
Marcello Mastroianni bumbles his way from surreal scene to outlandish situation. 
Tarantino may not be able to quite reach those heights himself, but I suppose that's a bit where he's coming from. His new film is more about a time and place, rather than a specific story.
So it's a love letter to post-Golden Age Hollywood.

Everyone who grew up in the 60/70s feels the vibe from it and that was probably the best thing about it. QT really went all in on details and the way people behaved. People were very different back then and much more direct, offensive and in your face than now, as people now are more subtile, sensitive, passive aggressive and harder to like. Making it harder to trust anyone than back then. Most likely because of the internet. Anyway, watching this movie made me feel a bit sad because of that. It made me miss the 70/80s and wish we never got internet. It has kind of screwed us all up a bit, becoming more stressed and weird and I don't know if I will live to see people relax again like in my youth. To younger people this movie won't make any sense. But to us over 50 it makes a lot of sense even if it actually doesn't. It's hard to explain. I wish QT had done some things differently as he had all this talent and money to make this movie. So in a way it feels a little disappointing after I watched it. Like an opportunity he screwed up by getting arty farty. Still a good movie you should watch, if only to maybe understand how things were before internet. One of his best technically. But it is far from his best movie, story wise. 6/10.

Tarantino is overated. IMO.

You watch some of his films and it feels like almost every single person walking down the street is a suspicious evil twisted motherfucker. Except for this film which, curiously, has a lighter tone. Also some scenes are way too violent, as in, you can almost hear the heavy breathing of Tarantino himslelf masturbating to the trauma unfolding in the scene, but without a necessary counterpoint of beauty or emotion to balance it make it all work as a grand story. Basically he is, or seems to be, a nihilist (which is okay) that has delved to deep into "the darkness" when filmaking and doesn't siccessfully balance that with "the light". Not even Pulp Fiction, which I also find overated. Many if his films are hardass characters, weird dialogue, weird funky/rock music, and of course violence.

This will probably get lost in the comments but I'll share my .02 anyways. My fav part was when he was on set filming the scene where Leo is playing a villain and holding the little girl hostage. Totally a Django unchained villain type performance coming from him. Anyways they cut the scene and everyone praised Leo for his performance. His Co star tells him that's the best acting she's ever seen. This hits Leo's character hard since just the night before he had a total alcohol induced identity crisis in his trailer feeling like an unraveling "has been" and thinking wtf am I doing. Anyways this girl's simple comment to him brings him to tears on set because it was just what he needed to ignite the tiniest spark he had left in his confidence. 

This scene choked me up since I feel like I can somewhat relate. I'm 31 years old with a wife and 4 year old daughter. I recently completely uprooted my 10 year, somewhat established career to start a new one as a software engineer. I'm in the middle of a 12 week full stack development program and thinking to myself wtf have I done. Learning html, css, SQL, python, Java, JavaScript, Ruby, rails, vim all within 12 weeks. This scene reminded me that it's ok to be in your 30s and restarting. And that I DO have what it takes if I just keep that spark lit for a little longer. A break through is just around the corner.

Just watched the movie and came here to check the review. Spoilers: Personally, I really enjoyed the film and it's casual vibe (I was expecting a lot more scenes, an Inglorious Basterds kinda pacing), but I don't think it had enough depth to justify the run time.

They could have made the ranch scene shorter and cut some other stuff and the very insulting Bruce Lee scene, the narration was weird and the narrative too loose. Considering that their big selling point is the ending twist, the movie could have literally started at 2 hours, once Rick and Cliff return to LA.


 The acting by Leo and Brad was top notch, one showing struggle while another showing swagger and Margot brought a certain innocence to Sharon's role but I wish she had more to do. Leo yelling while sipping a margarita was hilarious. Even the supporting performances by the Manson family members were amazing. 

The last 20 minutes of the film and that fictional twist was interesting. On one hand, the idea of a sweet ending where Sharon and her friends survive that horrendous incident would hit any viewer right in the feels. On a humour basis, Brad vs. Manson Family was the best scene of the film. But at the same time it seems like the movie manipulates you, because you're bearing through the slowee scenes to see how Tarentino deals with the murder scene. But he replaces it with this crazy fight scene and gives a fairy tale ending, which also seems like a cop out somehow. The film would only work if you actually knew about the Manson family murders, otherwise it falls flat.

Overall, certainly not as good a Tarentino film as Pulp Fiction or Kill Bill, but better than Kill Bill vol. 2 and Hateful Eight, it's also inferior to Djnago Unchained and Inglorious Basterds.

I have seen the movie. To me it really needs the audience to know what was the fate of Sharon Tate. And it also need you to recognize the Manson girls in order to build tension and suspense. If you do not know these things, the movie is not going to tell you till the very end. Which I kind of understand why they did not want to put any focus on the Manson family. But being as it is, you are just watching the main characters slowly get closer and closer to something you do not know what it is and have no clue how bad its going to turn. I guess this will be like an audience watching Titanic without the first scenes where they are told its all going to be a big tragedy. And I got myself thinking how would Titanic play if they did not set up immediately what is at stake. How would Titanic work if you did not know its a tragedy in waiting. I think this movie would improve if it started with some first scene with people talking what a BOMB was the Tate murder. And then you could still go the way the movie goes because it would still be "once upon a time". But knowing that the main characters are going to get involved with something incredibly big would make the movie much more meaningful. Like...if you knew there are going to be a bunch of hippie girls who are going to turn into serious killers…..all those funny scenes suddenly become serious. You suddenly fear for the stunt man because you know how dangerous those people can be.

I just got out of the movie theater and I agree, it certainly wasn't the best time I've had at the movies in 2019. Was it a bad movie, as some people are saying though? Heck no. There were some great lines, the two leads acted their hearts out, and it did feel like a love letter to classic Hollywood, from the sets, cinematography and dialogue to even the cameras and film equipment Tarantino used. That said, they could've cut about 30 minutes from this movie and it would've been just fine (or even better imo). The second act drags on forever, and you're not even sure what any of it means or is supossed to go. The last 15 minutes are great, but I don't feel like that was enough for me. It felt more like a slow-paced reflection of what 1969 Hollywood was like, and what it meant for some people, rather than an actual film with a plot.

I gotta agree with Jeremy here. This was not Tarantino's best, and it kills me to say that as one of his biggest fans. It had all the hallmarks of a Tarantino classic, but it just didn't have the plot to back it up. Tarantino is somewhat known for having flimsy plots loosely tied together by his unique style and the electrifying performances he gets out of his actors, but while this had all of that I just felt the film had no real direction until the end. I understand that to some extent the payoff of the end sequence is somewhat enhanced by the somewhat slow pace of the film beforehand. But, the fact remains that the film as a whole can at times be somewhat monotonous. In short, this is a good film, with amazing performances, quippy dialogue, Tarantino's unique visual flair, and it has one of the best endings I've seen in a film all year. Would I watch it again though? No, I probably wouldn't unless prompted by a friend.

I never thought that I would see the day where I would come out of a Tarantino film and be disheartened, but I have come to that day. The film is basically if you sit down with Quentin for 2 hours and 44 minutes and talk about all of his favorite movies and the history of cinema and of Hollywood and, then, decide to make a movie about it. I was thinking about what his tenth and allegedly last film will be. He’s said Star Trek and he’s mentioned a Kill Bill sequel. If he is really only making ten films, it can’t be both, or maybe it can. So, I think I have it figured out.
A Kill Bill-Star Trek crossover, framed by the narration of Jules from Pulp Fiction while he wanders the world, talking to strangers (lots of cameos). There. Everyone can be happy.
Actually, with this set-up, it can be done and make absolute sense within Quentin Tarantino’s movie-verse. Remember, Kill Bill is part of his movie-within-a-movie world. So, as he has said, Kill Bill is a film characters from Pulp Fiction or Reservoir Dogs would go see. Star Trek is obviously a known fictional universe. If Jules is narrating, he could just be making up a nonsensical Kill Bill-Star Trek crossover story with lots of campy martial arts fights and it wouldn’t have to make sense beyond that (try to imagine an Uma Thurman and William Shatner stand-off). It would just be Jules. No more. No less. Making weird shit up.
I would pay fifty bucks to see this film.
Also, this would free Quentin from any backlash from a miniature horde of angry Star Trek fans who may not dig an R-rated Star Trek film because it wouldn’t be canon anyway.

I hated Once Upon a Time in Hollywood
Here are some reasons why:
1. It is not like the trailers. The trailers make it feel like a high energy homage, maybe tongue in cheek at parts, and using real events as a backdrop for the fictional characters to be a part of or influenced by. Not so much, the story progresses forward very slowly (intentionally) with so many long, drawn out establishing shots, and walks to and from cars, and worst of all to me (but others may love), car rides to highlight music from the decade. If you took all of the car scenes and songs, many in one drive to a location, you would easily have a youtube music playlist to jam to. I don’t want to harp on some of the other elements because they become a bit more plot specific, but using the word you used, it becomes a bit indulgent. Intentionally showcasing street signs, billboards, magazines, sodas, beers, cigarettes, anything to evoke the era and show that they were able to get it or recreate it.
2. It is uneven tonally. There are times where it takes itself very seriously and it works, introspective characters responding to their situations in believable ways. At other times it becomes over the top, which makes sense in the movie making elements, but when the real world of the characters and the almost slapstick surrealism intermingle without it seeming like it is meant to as a storytelling piece and more rather for spectacle, I don’t buy it. On the filmmaking side as well, there was a seen in which the dialogue was so quiet we couldn’t hear two characters discussing other characters from a far, but all of the music was suitably loud, so that was off putting, and in a conversation between two characters, there were splices, but they didn’t read as advancements in the conversations, but closer to retakes, but it was a “real life” scene. If that is the point, more power, but I both was able to tell that was the case nor did it work for me.
3. Things I did like: seeing the behind the scenes elements of movie making and studio which came across in the trailer. Actors dressed up as other actors. Some splicing of contemporary actors into older films. There is a great scene illustrating serious actor prep. The little girl was wonderful and the payoff fantastic. Leo was great, Brad Pitt was charming, but was basically a more physical Rusty Ryan (from Ocean’s Eleven).
4. Some final not likes: no pay off on a character backstory, some Family Guy-esque quick flashbacks that happen in the middle of events, multiple times of excellent tension building for a false conclusion. Ultimately, I think some people may love it exactly as it is. I may literally be missing the entire point of the movie and thus my complaints are coming from a place of ignorance. However, I think the movie feels bloated and excessive, especially when compared to its trailer.
EDIT: I did misunderstand one aspect of the film, namely the ending, based on my age and lack of complete understanding of the '60s.

I really enjoyed this film! Is it one of QT’s best? Time will tell... I believe many will NOT like this movie... It’s long, boring at times... There are a few ways to describe this movie. One that comes to mind is this... Ever have someone tell you a joke? A really long Joke? Halfway thru the joke you say to yourself “Get to the punchline already!”... or “This better pay off in the end!”... Well, the payoff at the end of this long joke is worth it... To me anyway... Another way to describe this film is to say it’s a film about nothing... You get to hang out with Leo, Brad... Margo... Not much happens... And then some shit happens... I feel like the initial reactions to this will be negative overall, but over time, It’s weird absurd story and QT excellence will put this film in it’s place along side all of his greatest. Brad Pitt is tremendous in this! He proves once again that he is one of the greatest actors of all time. Everyone else is very good... Leo did a great job as always and Margo Robbie is a shining star as Sharon Tate. I could watch the last 15 minutes of this film over and over on a loop probably for days! The soundtrack is typical fun awesome QT stuff... I’m thrilled to have finally sat in a theater and watched something special... Something original... Not a sequel... Not a big dopey action movie... Not a quirky little over hyped art film... A real old fashioned Hollywood classic with big stars and interesting characters. And that ending!!!!!! Holy shit!!!! So I recommend this for my film buff friends who really appreciate QT and fine performances... And don’t mind a little truth bending of historical happenings (ala “Inglorious Basterds”).

Oscar might be kind to Mr. Pitt, Ms. Robbie and QT of course, perhaps for original screenplay. Picture and Director will likely get nods as well.

Fun fact... If you ever saw the great film “Shampoo” with Warren Beatty, he played the real life hairdresser Jay Sebring who was Sharon Tate’s boyfriend, who has a substantial role in this QT masterpiece.
