I didn't like this movie, Leonardo Dicaprio and Brad Pitt are really good, the 2 of them have great chemistry and I thought Tarantino did a great job recreating 1960's Hollywood, all the movie clips they show look as if their shot with 1960's cameras and I thought that was really impressive, and it was cool seeing a lot of other big actors pop up here and there, it really made it feel like legit Hollywood, however the movie overall just failed to engage me, mainly because their really is no overall story, it's pretty much just a series of scenes in which characters chat with each other and occasionally shoot a movie, it's not until the final part of the movie where something even remotely resembling a story comes into play, what I'm saying is that this movie overall was just kinda boring, it felt like Tarantino just wanted an excuse to tribute old 1950's-1960's Hollywood and didn't really want to make an entire movie, this feels like something he made purely for himself and not the audience, I will say this though, their's a scene at the end of the movie that I thought was fucking awesome, it's actually 1 of the coolest scenes I've ever seen in a Tarantino movie, which makes it all the more heartbreaking that it's attached to, in all honesty, a rather dull movie, this isn't a terrible movie by any means in fact it's really not that bad, it's just that as a Tarantino fan (He's my favorite director actually) I expected a little more, this felt like an experiment for him and even though it didn't work out I still admire him for trying, so yeah, this movie, while having that 1 sweet scene was just kind of a snooze-fest, the dialogue didn't really grab me like it usually does, the story isn't really there and this just felt like an excuse for Tarantino to play around with old school Hollywood stuff, so while not a terrible movie by any means I think it's a movie you can skip. 4/10

This might be one of those projects where he just wanted to go all out. You can't get old Tarantino back because those films were made by someone that was outside of the system and wanted to do things his way, and now you have a much older Quinton that has been  on the other side. This movie had a serious budget for QT to do whatever he wanted with. I actually saw a portion of this being filmed last summer in my town and they had vintage cars, shut down an entire block, remodeled the area just for one shot that might be on the screen for 2 seconds. This movie isn't a loveletter to the 60's, it's acknowledgement to the system that he understands it all now. This is the most self indulgent film of his because it is all about him at this stage in life.

One of the reasons I do not watch hardly any Youtube-"movie"-channels is because I feel like almost none of them have any appreciation, or sometimes even rudimentary knowledge, of film history. 

Some I get the sense they just don't give a damn.

Others I get the sense if they make a "Jaws"-reference they feel they've made a "deep cut".

This will make me sound like an asshole snob (to some people...) but the truth is it's got nothing to do with me. Cinema is something I care about and it sometimes bums me out that influential voices on Youtube seem to not care that there are decades of films which exist, pre-"Jaws".

There's over a hundred years worth of cinema to explore, and if you actually love the medium, it's a sincere reason to rejoice. Or should be.

1969 is 50 years ago...but in cinema terms, if you love cinema, that's irrelevant.

"Midnight Cowboy" won the Oscar for Best Picture that year. I re-watched it a few months ago and that film will still hit you in the gut, hard. As much as any film released today. 

If 1969 seems like distant film history only relevant to old men with canes, that's...kind of tragic.

It's just, for every reference I see on a popular "movie"-channel to Spielberg or Nolan (who are great) it'd be nice to sometimes also see a reference to Robert Aldritch. Or John Schlesinger. Or even Anatole Litvak.

I'll even take a stray Alan J Pakula every once in a while.

I just feel if you love cinema, truly love it, you should be enthusiastic (or at least curious) about its history. I don't feel I see enough of it on Youtube. It matters.

That said, Jahns is one of the few Youtube "movie"-channels I watch, primarily because his enthusiasm and sincerity (and wit) are worth watching.

And I enjoyed his commentary on Collider Movie Talk.

Clearly Jahns doesn't possess a "wealth" of film knowledge, but that's fine. He means what he says and is genuinely clever. That counts for a lot.

It puts him lightyears beyond precious, posturing blowhards, humming with transparently unearned authority, like "Your Movie Sucks" and his...ilk.

For everyone saying the Pitt / Bruce Lee fight was a dream, you're incorrect.  That was Pitt remembering WHY Kurt Russell won't let him on set anymore.  The distinction is that when Pitt drops Leo off, and Leo says Kurt Russell won't hire Pitt, that's for the Western he's shooting with Timothy Olyphant.  The flashback is for the Green Hornet show, which Leo mentions to Pacino he did a guest spot on.  Pitt is the stunt double for Leo on Green Hornet, where Bruce Lee was the co-star as Kato, which is why Pitt calls him Kato during the scene and Lee is wearing his classic Kato chauffeur uniform from the show.  So again, Pitt is remembering the last time Kurt Russell allowed him on set.  So when he snaps out of the flashback, he shrugs because he understands why Russell won't hire him back after that.

Once upon a Time in Hollywood is a very particular movie that won't please everyone and that is more than understandable. It lacks  characteristics of most successful films/tv series of our time. It doesn't even have an actual plot. It is Tarantino's personal style and perspective. Tarantino is one of the few directors that has the means, the money and the passion to create projects for the sake of his love for cinema and not for money or popularity. What I understood is that the story is exactly what the title indicates; a  'fairytale' in the Hollywood of the sixties. ....SPOILERS AHEAD....   our two main protagonists are the underdogs with failing careers in a magical land where only few make it and in the end they save the day by beating the shit out of the bad guys and give us a Happy Ending to a story that we all knew did not have it as the people in Tate's mansion were slaughtered in reality.  I enjoyed it, relishing DiCaprio and Pitt screentime and imagining that this is how people who make movies discuss about their work. However, as I said, I can get why many people would be bored or dissappointed.

Grace-- you totally missed the point about this movie.  At no point does Tarantino imply that Tate was complacent in her own murder or that if "real men" were there, they would of survived.  This is a fairy tale/wish fulfillment, just like Inglorious Basterds and Django Unchained.  Did a group of elite Jewish fighters make laughing stocks of the Nazis and kill Hitler?  No.  Did slaves making laughing stocks of their captors, get their freedom, and get violent revenge on their captors?  No.  But, in Tarantino's world they do.  And in OUATIH, the Manson murderers are comically thwarted.  Instead of Tate getting murdered, signalling the end of "classic" Hollywood, she survives and in Tarantino's world, perhaps the 60's Hollywood he so loves so much survives as well.  He doesn't hate women.  But, this is a story of fading Hollywood, through the prism of a fading star played by DiCaprio, wrapped around the friendship of two men, Pitt and DiCaprio.   The inference that Pitt killed is wife is just that, background to make him come across as dangerous.  That, and his take down of Bruce Lee, is all there to set up the ending.  It is so obvious it pains me that you entirely missed the point of this movie.

 But this idea of Hollywood really never was in reality. So Tarantino created a fairy tale for guys and maybe a few women in which the mythology is made flesh.  I think on that premise it works. 

True, the women, especially the girl who comes onto Booth, are objectified. Yet I appreciate the fact that like the men, the women could be on the make as well and be just as lusty and self interested as the men were. ( Armond White makes this point more eloquently in his review of the film.) Probably verboten to say in th era of Metoo but in the era of the Birth Control pill and free love probably perhaps this was more true then.  The scene in the car is an example. 

And as for the child actress? I saw her as an actress who was doing her best to be uber professional on set ( "I am not an actress!"), yet when she senses that Dalton is not ok she comforts him. I didn't see  anything untoward with that. It seemed to be one actor consoling another on the job during a time of trial. Creating an ensemble. When Rick picks himself up and aces the scene with the girl the payoff is them acting like they are in conflict but not (He apologizes to her for the throw, but she is just as game for improv, pointing at her elbow pad.

 Finally, (Spoiler)  Though I enjoyed the fantastical aspect of the end, I can see how Tarantino really amped up the absurdity of it for laughs. It nearly undercuts the rest of the film for me. I must say I was one of the few audience members in the audience who was laughing during that moment.  Most were silent. Still I enjoyed it.  Anywho, thanks for sharing your thoughts, Grace and voicing your displeasure respectfully and thoughtfully.

Thank you for this video. I often don't agree with your reviews, and sometimes, even your commentary, but I appreciate your right to fight for what you believe in and for your right to talk about your beliefs and about film. In this case, I really appreciate your thoughtful, well-explained commentary on this movie and the time period it erroneously depicts. I was a little disgusted about a lot of the concepts of this film, and I was not a fan of the choice of Robbie as Sharon Tate (nor the depiction of who Sharon was). I grew up in the late 60s/early 70s under the spectre of the rise of the serial killer, nuclear fears, the end of the Vietnam War, the rise of feminism, Watergate, the energy crisis, and the Bronx Zoo/Summer of Sam (I mean the Yankees and how NY was in the 70s). I have always been haunted by the Manson family and the gruesome Tate/LaBianca murders and how they changed Hollywood. How Terry Melcher's spurning of Manson's delusional estimation and belief in his own talent (and the little known fact that he also owed a ton of money to the Mob) caused one of the most horrific moments in history. As repulsive as Roman Polanski was (as well as his buddy Don Johnson, who never seemed to suffer the same fate as Polanski), there was never a real sense that he necessarily abused Sharon Tate. By all accounts, he truly adored her and was positively over the moon of her impending baby, and was crushed at her death. At any rate, I bring all this up because I am so disgusted at the constant need to feed Manson's ego (and bolster his insane followers' bloodlust), that Hollywood keeps feeding it with stories of him/them. Why not allow him to be forgotten, like should have happened. Yes, we all depict historical events, and we need to mark the impact that he had on these people and life then, but had everyone treated him as a nobody, he wouldn't have continued to wield the power he had, even from behind bars. Instead, people continue to glorify him. That is exactly what he wanted. Regardless, to think that too skinny, puny men would have taken care of the LSD-fueled, hopped up savages that were the Family, is ridiculous. It is positively preposterous (and Bruce Lee would have kicked their behinds six ways to Sunday).

SPOILERS: I appreciate your passion, Grace. I disagree with a lot of your takes. I enjoyed the movie quite a bit and plan to give it a second watch to see if any of your points take me in a different direction. I really enjoyed Rick and Cliff’s relationship and the story of their career arc. Areas that I disagree on. The whole foot thing is just QT and his known foot obsession. The little girl actress really seemed to me like an honest moment where she was being sincere in her reaction and commentary but not at all sexual. And for the ending..I did not see it at all as a slight to Sharon Tate or the others who were murdered. Much like Inglorious Basterds, the ending felt like an exercise in catharsis for the audience. It’s not QTs fault if viewers are unaware of the Manson murders as most are very aware going into the movie and I think most will appreciate that the 3 members of the family received what they did. The final aerial shot of Rick being greeted by Sharon and the other 3 was beautiful to me. Rick got what he was hoping for with a foot in the door with his new-Hollywood neighbors and it was a way for QT to shine a light on the lives of Sharon and the others and how inviting and loving they were in contrast to the Manson family.   If anything, I wish there had been more of a dig on Polanski who is truly vile.

Once Upon a Time in Hollywood is such a unique film going experience. The meticulous recreation of 1969 Hollywood and the brilliant sweeping shots Tarantino uses to romanticize it is endlessly fascinating. Tarantino finally examines the melancholy side of nostalgia and the result is heartwarming and powerful. It is not a movie for everyone. It’s a slow burn that’s deliberately paced but teases the inevitable shocking ending every step of the way. I loved it. A masterclass of direction. I do think it lacks Tarantino’s signature dialogue though. I needed my Jules/Vincent “Royale with Cheese”, “Foot massage”, “Walk the earth” scenes between Pitt/DiCaprio that showed their bromance on fully display. The movie also needed more DaKota Fanning (who is remarkable in her one scene), Margot Robbie (the heart and soul of the movie), and Margaret Qualley (explosively temptous and creepy at the same time). That woulda made it the perfect movie.

I felt the exact same way leaving the theater last night - because I thoroughly enjoyed this movie...and it feels wrong. Aesthetically, this movie is perfect, and it sucks you into the glitz and glamour of 1960s Hollywood. And that I think is Tarantino's point: he's saying that Hollywood should've stayed that way. It's his revenge fairytale, hence the movie's title. He's giving us the ending we're all led to believe in popular Hollywood media: that everything is happy, the bad guys died, and DiCaprio and Robbie can have a lovely meeting once the fighting's done. I have the same fear that uninformed moviegoers will believe the story as true. I put in my review on Facebook that people should do research and have general knowledge before seeing this movie. It's easy to think that after the Manson Family murdered Sharon Tate, Hollywood was shocked to its core and then responded over time with darker and edgier films. The glamour and the fantasy disappeared. Of course, that presents the main problem, because Tarantino is so hell-bent on changing history to fit HIS vision of what he thinks Hollywood should've stayed like. And you're right: he's not critiquing or even playing with the trope of the "strong male hero" coming in to save the day...he just presents it. Though I can't speak of or for the female perspective, I thought Sharon Tate's scene enjoying herself in the movie theater was a reflection of how movie stars look for more than just validation from critics - she's experiencing her movie with a general audience and happy that they're positively responding to her comedy. Again, I can't speak of that scene from a female perspective and what it was like for you to watch it, but that's what I thought he was getting at - it seemed more than just objectification. Overall, I really liked this movie...but something feels wrong in saying that. I like the conversations this movie is starting, which in turn makes me like it more...but it feels weird to enjoy someone blatantly changing history, especially when it was such a tragic and intimately shocking story.
